Moreover, the so-called information countries,

23:19.000 --> 23:22.000
this will be the third argument against,

23:22.000 --> 23:27.000
which are the leaders in the information sphere,

23:27.000 --> 23:29.000
at the same time,

23:29.000 --> 23:32.000
they are also the most resource-consuming.

23:32.000 --> 23:35.000
More than half of the resources on the planet Earth

23:35.000 --> 23:39.000
are consumed by these so-called information countries.

23:39.000 --> 23:44.000
The fourth criterion, which I highlight,

23:44.000 --> 23:47.000
is that despite the unprecedented growth

23:47.000 --> 23:50.000
of advertising and television in the economy,

23:50.000 --> 23:53.000
nevertheless, the economic efficiency

23:53.000 --> 23:58.000
of these phenomena is more than dubious.

23:58.000 --> 24:01.000
Indeed, the yellow press, in fact,

24:01.000 --> 24:04.000
has flooded all our kiosks and counters.

24:04.000 --> 24:07.000
Nevertheless, what information value,

24:07.000 --> 24:10.000
that is, they carry some information load,

24:10.000 --> 24:14.000
but the economic value is very dubious.

24:14.000 --> 24:17.000
Therefore, the key answer to the question

24:17.000 --> 24:20.000
about the growing role of economic information

24:20.000 --> 24:22.000
and other information products

24:22.000 --> 24:24.000
should be, first of all,

24:24.000 --> 24:27.000
the answer to the question of what society

24:27.000 --> 24:30.000
we want to build, form or create.

24:31.000 --> 24:33.000
If we want to create a society

24:33.000 --> 24:36.000
that will consume only information products,

24:36.000 --> 24:39.000
and access to valuable things,

24:39.000 --> 24:42.000
such as oil and gas,

24:42.000 --> 24:46.000
will be closed to the main members of society

24:46.000 --> 24:50.000
and will be offered only to the chosen ones,

24:50.000 --> 24:53.000
then it will be very beneficial

24:53.000 --> 24:56.000
to call our society informational.

24:56.000 --> 25:00.000
In fact, here you create your information products,

25:00.000 --> 25:03.000
here you have a show, cartoons,

25:03.000 --> 25:05.000
please consume them,

25:05.000 --> 25:08.000
but do not pay attention to the resources,

25:08.000 --> 25:11.000
the real resources that are valuable.

25:11.000 --> 25:14.000
The fourth argument against this

25:14.000 --> 25:18.000
is the fact that despite the unprecedented growth,

25:18.000 --> 25:21.000
the unprecedented growth of advertising

25:21.000 --> 25:24.000
and television in the economy,

25:24.000 --> 25:28.000
which should be a sign of an informational society,

25:28.000 --> 25:34.000
in general, is a dubious economic purpose and role.

25:34.000 --> 25:38.000
Therefore, I draw to the intermediate conclusion

25:38.000 --> 25:41.000
that the key answer to the question

25:41.000 --> 25:44.000
about the growing role of economic information

25:44.000 --> 25:46.000
and other information products

25:46.000 --> 25:49.000
should be the answer to the question

25:50.000 --> 25:53.000
what kind of society we want to build,

25:53.000 --> 25:55.000
form and create.

25:55.000 --> 25:58.000
If we want to create a society

25:58.000 --> 26:01.000
where there will be an economic price tag

26:01.000 --> 26:04.000
for each product and service

26:04.000 --> 26:07.000
for which we have to pay

26:07.000 --> 26:10.000
and there will be nothing free,

26:10.000 --> 26:13.000
as it was in our past societies,

26:13.000 --> 26:16.000
then this society will be a good example

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
for some, especially economists,

26:19.000 --> 26:22.000
and those who have access

26:22.000 --> 26:26.000
to the real sources of income of the country,

26:26.000 --> 26:29.000
it will be beneficial for them

26:29.000 --> 26:32.000
to call our society informational.

26:32.000 --> 26:35.000
However, a lot, especially in terms of social,

26:35.000 --> 26:38.000
especially for those categories of people

26:38.000 --> 26:41.000
who are involved only in public life

26:41.000 --> 26:44.000
or who leave it, that is, the older generation,

26:44.000 --> 26:47.000
will not be able to do it for free.

26:47.000 --> 26:50.000
Therefore, the growing role of economic purpose

26:50.000 --> 26:53.000
or economic role of information products

26:53.000 --> 26:56.000
is not quite the right goal

26:56.000 --> 26:59.000
of the development of society.

26:59.000 --> 27:02.000
A lot in our society should be done

27:02.000 --> 27:05.000
in the non-economic sphere,

27:05.000 --> 27:08.000
outside the access of economists

27:08.000 --> 27:11.000
to the fact that they put price tags

27:11.000 --> 27:14.000
on information products and services.

27:14.000 --> 27:17.000
The next criterion is a cultural criterion.

27:17.000 --> 27:20.000
Each of us knows that the circulation of information

27:20.000 --> 27:23.000
in social life has increased enormously.

27:23.000 --> 27:26.000
In fact, we live in such a media society

27:26.000 --> 27:29.000
in which neither our fathers nor our grandfathers lived.

27:29.000 --> 27:32.000
However, despite the increasing amount of information

27:32.000 --> 27:35.000
in the cultural sphere,

27:35.000 --> 27:38.000
we still have a lot of information

27:38.000 --> 27:41.000
and we have a paradox.

27:41.000 --> 27:44.000
The paradox is that the information explosion

27:44.000 --> 27:47.000
led to the dissolution of meaning.

27:47.000 --> 27:50.000
Jean Baudillard,

27:50.000 --> 27:53.000
one of the founders of postmodernism,

27:53.000 --> 27:56.000
wrote well about this.

27:56.000 --> 27:59.000
In 1983, he wrote

27:59.000 --> 28:02.000
that the amount of information is increasing,

28:02.000 --> 28:05.000
but the meaning is decreasing.

28:05.000 --> 28:08.000
We live among these simulacra.

28:08.000 --> 28:11.000
Simula is a Latin word for pretending,

28:11.000 --> 28:14.000
pretending or a copy,

28:14.000 --> 28:17.000
that is, an original.

28:17.000 --> 28:20.000
In fact, from the point of view of postmodernists,

28:20.000 --> 28:23.000
I am advertising my image.

28:23.000 --> 28:26.000
In this case, it is an image of a tutor

28:26.000 --> 28:29.000
on the MBS Start program.

28:29.000 --> 28:32.000
We are surrounded by these simulacra.

28:32.000 --> 28:35.000
There is nothing real around us.

28:35.000 --> 28:38.000
These are idealized,

28:38.000 --> 28:41.000
sign products of culture

28:41.000 --> 28:44.000
that have lost their connection

28:44.000 --> 28:47.000
with real objects.

28:47.000 --> 28:50.000
This is what a simulacra is in the usual sense.

28:50.000 --> 28:53.000
It is the creative specialists

28:53.000 --> 28:56.000
who have self-reflection,

28:56.000 --> 28:59.000
self-awareness and are very productive

28:59.000 --> 29:02.000
and create this culture of copies,

29:02.000 --> 29:05.000
easily distort,

29:05.000 --> 29:08.000
interpret and break their original meaning.

29:08.000 --> 29:11.000
This is why it is so popular

29:11.000 --> 29:14.000
on television

29:14.000 --> 29:17.000
or in the corporate environment

29:17.000 --> 29:20.000
various shows, kitsch, analogies.

29:20.000 --> 29:23.000
But we must remember one thing.

29:23.000 --> 29:26.000
Whatever society we live in,

29:26.000 --> 29:29.000
it lives on its moral and ethical principles

29:29.000 --> 29:32.000
that have nothing to do with information.

29:32.000 --> 29:35.000
Remember them.

29:35.000 --> 29:38.000
Namely,

29:38.000 --> 29:41.000
you live for yourself and let others live.

29:41.000 --> 29:44.000
All people are created equal.

29:44.000 --> 29:47.000
This is my country,

29:47.000 --> 29:50.000
whether it is right or not, and so on.

29:50.000 --> 29:53.000
What did the century of information give us?

29:53.000 --> 29:56.000
Time is money.

29:56.000 --> 29:59.000
Who owns information, owns the world.

29:59.000 --> 30:02.000
I think that we can hardly build a normal society

30:02.000 --> 30:05.000
on these principles.

30:05.000 --> 30:08.000
The next criterion is related to the occupation.

30:08.000 --> 30:11.000
This is the last criterion

30:11.000 --> 30:14.000
that we will consider as a sign of an information society.

30:14.000 --> 30:17.000
It is related to the structure of the population's occupation

30:17.000 --> 30:20.000
and the models of changes observed.

30:20.000 --> 30:23.000
It is known that in Western Europe, Japan, North America

30:23.000 --> 30:26.000
more than 70% of the workforce

30:26.000 --> 30:29.000
is engaged in the service sector.

30:29.000 --> 30:32.000
So, the so-called white-collar work prevails.

30:32.000 --> 30:35.000
It will be a little more difficult

30:35.000 --> 30:38.000
to deal with this criterion

30:38.000 --> 30:41.000
than with the innovation and technology.

30:41.000 --> 30:44.000
Because here not some technology

30:44.000 --> 30:47.000
affects the brain,

30:47.000 --> 30:50.000
but the information is promoted in the brain.

30:50.000 --> 30:53.000
How is it produced in the field of occupation

30:53.000 --> 30:56.000
and how is it realized through education and experience.

30:56.000 --> 30:59.000
It is believed that the driving force of the modern economy

30:59.000 --> 31:02.000
will be people whose main ability

31:02.000 --> 31:05.000
is to use information.

31:05.000 --> 31:08.000
It will be system analysts,

31:08.000 --> 31:11.000
niche finders, designers, experts, and so on.

31:11.000 --> 31:14.000
The common sense remains constant.

31:14.000 --> 31:17.000
The main drivers in the economy are those

31:17.000 --> 31:20.000
whose work requires the creation and use of information.

31:20.000 --> 31:23.000
Therefore, it is quite logical

31:23.000 --> 31:26.000
that a coal miner is an industrialist,

31:26.000 --> 31:29.000
and an expert is already a member of the information society.

31:32.000 --> 31:35.000
So, in order to consider the criteria

31:35.000 --> 31:38.000
related to the super-capacity,

31:38.000 --> 31:41.000
we will analyze a small business case.

31:41.000 --> 31:44.000
In September 2006,

31:44.000 --> 31:47.000
a case was handled

31:47.000 --> 31:50.000
with the state corporation Comcor.

31:50.000 --> 31:53.000
The fact is that this corporation

31:53.000 --> 31:56.000
created a call center in Tula

31:56.000 --> 31:59.000
for 600 agency places,

31:59.000 --> 32:02.000
the largest in Russia.

32:02.000 --> 32:05.000
In Moscow, where the minimum wage of operators

32:05.000 --> 32:08.000
is 15-20 thousand rubles,

32:08.000 --> 32:11.000
and the minimum wage of a licensed agent

32:11.000 --> 32:14.000
is 40 thousand rubles,

32:14.000 --> 32:17.000
it is not profitable for businessmen

32:17.000 --> 32:20.000
to pay such salaries.

32:20.000 --> 32:23.000
In addition, the current situation is high.

32:23.000 --> 32:26.000
People work for half a year and leave.

32:26.000 --> 32:29.000
The company Comcor and its director Grishin

32:29.000 --> 32:32.000
chose Tula as the least

32:32.000 --> 32:35.000
outsourced by the region.

32:35.000 --> 32:38.000
The company offered them

32:38.000 --> 32:41.000
from 8 to 12 thousand rubles

32:41.000 --> 32:44.000
for those who initially

32:44.000 --> 32:47.000
became operators,

32:47.000 --> 32:50.000
and for advanced operators

32:50.000 --> 32:53.000
from 16 thousand rubles.

32:53.000 --> 32:56.000
This is very profitable

32:56.000 --> 32:59.000
for both Tula and Comcor owners.

32:59.000 --> 33:02.000
The company offered

33:02.000 --> 33:05.000
from 8 to 12 thousand rubles

33:05.000 --> 33:08.000
for those who initially

33:08.000 --> 33:11.000
became operators,

33:11.000 --> 33:14.000
and for advanced operators

33:14.000 --> 33:17.000
from 16 thousand rubles.

33:17.000 --> 33:20.000
By the end of 2007,

33:20.000 --> 33:23.000
they planned to complete

33:23.000 --> 33:26.000
all the workplaces,

33:26.000 --> 33:29.000
that is, to hire 1,500 operators.

33:29.000 --> 33:32.000
But they hired 1,500 new information workers

33:32.000 --> 33:35.000
who came from non-information spheres.

33:35.000 --> 33:38.000
The average salary of 12-16 thousand rubles per month

33:38.000 --> 33:41.000
is unlikely to allow them

33:41.000 --> 33:44.000
to significantly change their lifestyle

33:44.000 --> 33:47.000
and join the world of the chosen ones,

33:47.000 --> 33:50.000
that is, specialists of high technologies.

33:50.000 --> 33:53.000
This is understandable.

33:53.000 --> 33:56.000
In Russia, there is a double inflation

33:56.000 --> 33:59.000
All the management decisions

33:59.000 --> 34:02.000
that were made

34:02.000 --> 34:05.000
to transfer business from Moscow to Tula

34:05.000 --> 34:08.000
have remained unchanged

34:08.000 --> 34:11.000
since the pre-information era.

34:11.000 --> 34:14.000
More is done, less is done.

34:14.000 --> 34:17.000
Moreover, it could be assumed

34:17.000 --> 34:20.000
that if the work in the call center

34:20.000 --> 34:23.000
would allow operators

34:23.000 --> 34:26.000
to grow to the level of the director,

34:26.000 --> 34:29.000
then we would have some information society

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
because the director can allow himself

34:32.000 --> 34:35.000
to change his laptop for a year or two,

34:35.000 --> 34:38.000
have access to high-value knowledge,

34:38.000 --> 34:41.000
how to organize a project, etc.

34:41.000 --> 34:44.000
But the fact is that the harmonious

34:44.000 --> 34:47.000
functioning of society itself

34:47.000 --> 34:50.000
does not imply the increase of people

34:50.000 --> 34:53.000
in the position of the director.

34:53.000 --> 34:56.000
Not everyone should be a director.

34:56.000 --> 34:59.000
That is why we have the fact

34:59.000 --> 35:02.000
that the work of operators

35:02.000 --> 35:05.000
is routine in relation to the work of the director.

35:05.000 --> 35:08.000
The same can be said about programmers

35:08.000 --> 35:11.000
and computer scientists.

35:11.000 --> 35:14.000
These professions are a symbol

35:14.000 --> 35:17.000
of our information age.

35:18.000 --> 35:21.000
But we have a phenomenon of computer crime

35:21.000 --> 35:24.000
among programmers and computer scientists.

35:24.000 --> 35:27.000
This is a proof that the knowledge

35:27.000 --> 35:30.000
that was ingrained in their heads

35:30.000 --> 35:33.000
did not affect their motives.

35:33.000 --> 35:36.000
We all know the hacking,

35:36.000 --> 35:39.000
the theft of business cards,

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
the theft of credit cards, etc.

35:42.000 --> 35:45.000
All this is done by programmers

35:45.000 --> 35:48.000
who have acquired some information knowledge.

35:48.000 --> 35:51.000
Their motives and actions

35:51.000 --> 35:54.000
have remained unchanged.

35:54.000 --> 35:57.000
Moreover, we can say that despite the increase

35:57.000 --> 36:00.000
in the number of programmers and computer scientists,

36:00.000 --> 36:03.000
there has been no less increase

36:03.000 --> 36:06.000
in the number of social workers.

36:06.000 --> 36:09.000
And their work, although it is more noble,

36:09.000 --> 36:12.000
is paid less in society.

36:12.000 --> 36:15.000
They use less information

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
and less information products

36:18.000 --> 36:21.000
than programmers and computer scientists.

36:21.000 --> 36:24.000
In any case, we need to analyze

36:24.000 --> 36:27.000
the information work of a particular worker

36:27.000 --> 36:30.000
and determine the quality of his work,

36:30.000 --> 36:33.000
which will allow him to occupy

36:33.000 --> 36:36.000
a certain niche in the hierarchy of society.

36:36.000 --> 36:39.000
We also need to determine the responsibility

36:39.000 --> 36:42.000
of the information society.

36:42.000 --> 36:45.000
Only then can we understand

36:45.000 --> 36:48.000
whether the criteria of information occupation

36:48.000 --> 36:51.000
can be a sign of an information society.

36:51.000 --> 36:54.000
Today, it can be said that society

36:54.000 --> 36:57.000
is already pointless to divide

36:57.000 --> 37:00.000
into workers, collective farmers or intelligentsia.

37:00.000 --> 37:03.000
Moreover, even such high-status groups

37:03.000 --> 37:06.000
of people as owners or entrepreneurs

37:06.000 --> 37:09.000
are becoming a driving force of our society.

37:09.000 --> 37:12.000
In many countries, including our country,

37:12.000 --> 37:15.000
the driving force has already become professionals,

37:15.000 --> 37:18.000
that is, elite groups of people,

37:18.000 --> 37:21.000
the basis of their activities is service,

37:21.000 --> 37:24.000
that is, service of a certain area of activity.

37:24.000 --> 37:27.000
Further, certification,

37:27.000 --> 37:30.000
the presence of some status documents,

37:30.000 --> 37:33.000
the portfolio of some implemented projects

37:33.000 --> 37:36.000
and the ability to achieve some goals,

37:36.000 --> 37:39.000
in particular business goals.

37:39.000 --> 37:42.000
We see that none of the criteria

37:42.000 --> 37:45.000
of information, technological,

37:45.000 --> 37:48.000
economic, cultural or occupation

37:48.000 --> 37:51.000
can be considered as full-fledged concepts

37:51.000 --> 37:54.000
by which we can determine our society

37:54.000 --> 37:57.000
and its activities.

37:57.000 --> 38:00.000
We need to understand

38:00.000 --> 38:03.000
that the increase in the amount of information

38:03.000 --> 38:06.000
cannot mean that we are moving

38:06.000 --> 38:09.000
into a high-quality society.

38:09.000 --> 38:12.000
Therefore, we must answer the question

38:12.000 --> 38:15.000
whether the information that surrounds me

38:15.000 --> 38:18.000
is useful,

38:18.000 --> 38:21.000
what can it give me in the future,

38:21.000 --> 38:24.000
whether it is a threat to me.

38:24.000 --> 38:27.000
We need to understand

38:27.000 --> 38:30.000
that information is not structured

38:30.000 --> 38:33.000
by the power of the information.

38:33.000 --> 38:36.000
At the same time,

38:36.000 --> 38:39.000
the information that we can structure,

38:39.000 --> 38:42.000
manage, analyze,

38:42.000 --> 38:45.000
becomes less and less

38:45.000 --> 38:48.000
in the weight of the general information.

38:48.000 --> 38:51.000
This is the threat

38:51.000 --> 38:54.000
that information brings us.

38:54.000 --> 38:57.000
We can recall the fathers of the theory of information,

38:57.000 --> 39:00.000
namely Claude Shannon and Warren Weaver,

39:00.000 --> 39:03.000
who in 1949 gave the definition of information

39:03.000 --> 39:06.000
as the quantitative estimate of the probability

39:06.000 --> 39:09.000
of the frequency of the appearance of symbols

39:09.000 --> 39:12.000
associated with the concept of a bit,

39:12.000 --> 39:15.000
that is, a binary signal that takes values 0 and 1.

39:15.000 --> 39:18.000
Unfortunately, such a definition of information

39:18.000 --> 39:21.000
is useful for engineers in communications,

39:21.000 --> 39:24.000
but it is not useful for us

39:24.000 --> 39:27.000
to understand the meaning and value of information.

39:27.000 --> 39:30.000
Information, in fact, exists

39:30.000 --> 39:33.000
as space and time exist,

39:33.000 --> 39:36.000
as commodity-money relations or equivalent relations,

39:36.000 --> 39:39.000
and other relations.

39:39.000 --> 39:42.000
We can express ourselves more clearly.

39:42.000 --> 39:45.000
Information is a condition of existence.

39:45.000 --> 39:48.000
But what?

39:48.000 --> 39:51.000
We are surrounded by different objects of reality

39:51.000 --> 39:54.000
that we reflect in the senses,

39:54.000 --> 39:57.000
calculate, model,

39:57.000 --> 40:00.000
that is, we transform them into some data.

40:00.000 --> 40:03.000
Data in Latin is a calculation.

40:03.000 --> 40:06.000
In fact, it is an idealized representation

40:06.000 --> 40:09.000
of the environment or reality

40:09.000 --> 40:12.000
in some formalized form,

40:12.000 --> 40:15.000
suitable for transmission and processing

40:15.000 --> 40:18.000
Idealization occurs through some language

40:18.000 --> 40:21.000
consisting of some signs,

40:21.000 --> 40:24.000
their structures, their relations, etc.

40:24.000 --> 40:27.000
All this is called a syntax of the language,

40:27.000 --> 40:30.000
that is, a syntax of the Greek component.

40:30.000 --> 40:33.000
These data that we receive

40:33.000 --> 40:36.000
and transform into the senses

40:36.000 --> 40:39.000
can be combined into metadata

40:39.000 --> 40:42.000
that explains other data

40:42.000 --> 40:45.000
and can be used to create a semantic

40:45.000 --> 40:48.000
that is derived from the Greek word

40:48.000 --> 40:51.000
meaning.

40:51.000 --> 40:54.000
Semantic is a connection between

40:54.000 --> 40:57.000
the syntax signs and objects of reality

40:57.000 --> 41:00.000
that these signs describe and reflect.

41:00.000 --> 41:03.000
The interaction process itself,

41:03.000 --> 41:06.000
when either reflection or data exchange occurs,

41:06.000 --> 41:09.000
is called communication.

41:09.000 --> 41:12.000
If we perform some operations on data,

41:12.000 --> 41:15.000
for example, assign some value to some data,

41:15.000 --> 41:18.000
it will mean connecting them with other data

41:18.000 --> 41:21.000
and they already become some indicators

41:21.000 --> 41:24.000
or attributes,

41:24.000 --> 41:27.000
that is, significant characteristics

41:27.000 --> 41:30.000
of the properties of the object

41:30.000 --> 41:33.000
that we can measure, understand,

41:33.000 --> 41:36.000
highlight, study.

41:36.000 --> 41:39.000
There is a very significant point here,

41:39.000 --> 41:42.000
which is the basis for understanding

41:42.000 --> 41:45.000
the subsequent development of the forms of information.

41:45.000 --> 41:48.000
It is necessary to understand that

41:48.000 --> 41:51.000
the indicators of the attributes,

41:51.000 --> 41:54.000
both the indicators themselves and the operations

41:54.000 --> 41:57.000
above them, are just a portion of information

41:57.000 --> 42:00.000
that we can judge

42:00.000 --> 42:03.000
about the essence of the object and its semantics,

42:03.000 --> 42:06.000
that is, about its meaning.

